":"Mount Wise, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"BRITT","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: ethnic name for a Celtic-speaking Briton or a Breton, from Middle English <i>brit</i>, <i>bret</i>, Old French <i>bret</i> (see   Brett  ).","German: from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Brixius</i> (see   Brice  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Britting","meanings":["South German: patronymic from   Britt  .","American shortened form of South German <b>Brittinger</b>, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Brett","meanings":["English (West Midlands): from Middle English <i>brat</i> ‘cloak of coarse cloth’ (Old English <i>bratt</i>), possibly denoting a maker or habitual wearer of such garments. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Brett  .","Swedish and Norwegian: from the Old Norse personal name <i>Brattr</i> meaning ‘majestic, proud’ (also, of places, ‘steep’). See also   Bradt  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret BRITT was born about 1390, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Britt, was 14 and her mother, Margaret Callahan, was 36. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Thomas Wyse. She died in 1429, in Mount Wise, Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40, and was buried in Stoke Damerel, Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1390–1429":"umbes 1390–1429","1375–1411":"1375–1411","1390–1429":"1390–1429","1330–1421":"1330–1421","1429–1460":"1429–1460","1429–1505":"1429–1505","1377–1404":"1377–1404","1355–1429":"1355–1429","1374":"1374","1330":"1330","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1411":"1411","1421":"1421","1355":"1355","1377":